Nice article. I thought it was going to be superficial and rehashing common ideas but the author covers a lot of ground and languages in this overview.<p>Of all the languages I&#x27;ve encountered with null/Option/Optional/Maybe in, the one I think is the most interesting is Ceylon.<p>Ceylon supports sum types, so you can say that a type is &quot;Account&quot; (non nullable) or &quot;Account|Null&quot; (which can be abbreviated to &quot;Account?&quot;).<p>The compiler will not let you dereference a nullable type, you will have to switch/type cast it first:<p><pre><code>    Account? account = ...
    if (exists account) {
      // account has type Account, safe to dereference
    } else {
      // account has type Null, can&#x27;t dereference
    }
</code></pre>
<a href="http://ceylon-lang.org/" rel="nofollow">http://ceylon-lang.org/</a>
